T1  - Employee Creativity in Taiwan: An Application of Role Identity Theory
AU  - Farmer, Steven M.
AU  - Tierney, Pamela
AU  - Kung-Mcintyre, Kate
Y1  - 2003/10/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/30040653
DO  - 10.5465/30040653
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 618
EP  - 630
VL  - 46
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study tests a model of creative role identity for a sample of Taiwanese employees. Results showed creative role identity was predicted by perceived coworker creativity expectations, self-views of creative behaviors, and high levels of exposure to U.S. culture. Creativity was highest when a strong creative role identity was paired with perceptions that the employing organization valued creative work. Implications for managers and future creativity research are discussed.
AB  - This study tests a model of creative role identity for a sample of Taiwanese employees. Results showed creative role identity was predicted by perceived coworker creativity expectations, self-views of creative behaviors, and high levels of exposure to U.S. culture. Creativity was highest when a strong creative role identity was paired with perceptions that the employing organization valued creative work. Implications for managers and future creativity research are discussed.
